    <title>Combined summary - Roadmap to getting users onto SPV clients</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T09:39:44.931332+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-December/002066.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>There are ongoing discussions on the Bitcoin Development mailing list about improving the presentation of Bitcoin wallet options to users. Currently, bitcoin.org recommends downloading the full client, but suggestions for alternative options such as cloud services and fast-start paths with recommended wallet apps are discussed.The need for full nodes in the Bitcoin network is also debated, with some suggesting that promoting Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) clients to new users may be a better solution. However, there are concerns about compromising security and decentralization. The ideal first client for new Bitcoin users should be usable within a couple of minutes, support multiple operating systems, and use deterministic wallets that can produce a permanent backup.Efforts are underway to improve the Satoshi client and encourage new users to start using Bitcoin even if they don't support it initially. MultiBit is considered an excellent choice, but there are concerns about its staffing if it becomes the de facto client for new users. Overall, the community is working to find a balance between user experience and network security.There is a debate about whether every user needs to run a full node or if having a vast number of users supported by a smaller number of committed nodes is possible, similar to the Tor network. However, it is agreed that it is important to send a clear message to users to support the network and find ways to improve the user experience without reducing the model's robustness.The proposal for Alan's UTxO meta-chain has become easier to implement, but there are still challenges ahead. There is also a discussion on key structure disagreements, meta-chain proposals, and the challenges that need to be overcome before the UTxO meta-chain proposal can become a reality.There are ongoing discussions on the Bitcoin-development mailing list regarding the user experience of SPV (Simplified Payment Verification) clients and the need for full nodes in the network. Some users are facing difficulties with understanding the purpose of Bitcoin, downloading wallets, sending Bitcoins without fees, and synchronization, which highlights the importance of listening to end-users to refine software engineering requirements.The Bitcoin-development mailing list discusses the need for a better way to present Bitcoin wallet options to users. Will suggests directing users to a vetted list of cloud services as an alternative option with a lower entry cost than any client, and Mike proposes presenting users with a fast-start path by recommending wallet apps A or B.The proposed UTxO meta-chain could allow the Satoshi client to operate with greater than or equal to SPV level of security during initial block download, but there are challenges ahead. These include inventing and reaching consensus on a normative data structure, as well as writing implementations of required operations.Alan Reiner and Greg Maxwell express differing opinions on the risk of centralization through promoting a SPV node to new users. Alan argues that there is no real risk, as long as all full nodes are full-validation, and that connectedness is the real metric of concern rather than the number of nodes. Greg disagrees, stating that there are DOS attack risks from sybil attackers and that a healthy darknet of private authenticated peerings between miners and other likely targets can address those risks.Gary Rowe expressed his thoughts on the user experience of SPV clients. According to him, users expect an "instant-on" experience when using Bitcoin, and SPV clients deliver on that expectation. He believes that once users have a great initial experience, their interest in Bitcoin is reinforced, and they tend to explore further into the economic theory behind it. Many decide to install the full node out of a sense of community contribution to the security of the network. Rowe suggests that having a hybrid mode of SPV first then full node second should be something that a user has control over, as Bitcoin should not be perceived as a drain on their computing resources.</summary>
